Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
If not already completed Defendant must submit to booking at Sheriff's Dept prior to release.
Defendant shall give written notice prior to any change in address or telephone number to the Clerk of this Court and Defense Attorney.

10:43 AM court calls cases: 20CT19, 22CF19, 22CM17 Defendant Donald Edwin Warren appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Karl J. Kelz in court for State of Wisconsin. Court goes over the cases and charges. Defendant makes statements and comments. DA Kelz gives bond recommendations in each case. DA Kelz requests a $1,000 cash bond in case 22CF19 and case 22CM17. DA Kelz requests a signature bond in the amount of $1,500 in case 20CT19. Court orders bonds in the amount of $1,000 in cases 22CF19 and case 22CM17 and to reinstate the signature bond in case 20CT19. Notice of right to attorney given to Defendant. Court orders the initial appearances adjourned to 11/15/2022 at 10:00 AM.  DA Kelz moves to quash warrants in each case. So ordered by the court.
